8–1509","1460–Male":"1460–Deceased","1478":"1478","1460":"1460","1509":"1509","about 1460":"about 1460","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived on or by a hill, from Middle English <i>hill</i>, <i>hell</i>, <i>hull</i> ‘hill’ (Old English <i>hyll</i>). Compare   Hiller  . This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English: possibly in some cases from the personal name <i>Hille</i>, a pet form of some name such as   Hilger   or   Hillary  .","German: from a short form of   Hildebrand   or any of a variety of other names, male and female, containing ancient Germanic <i>hild</i> ‘battle’ as the first element."],"variants":[{"name":"Hillock","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) small hill’, from Middle English <i>hillok</i>, a diminutive of <i>hille</i> (Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’). See   Hill  ."]},{"name":"Hills","meanings":["English: variant of   Hill   with genitival <i>-s</i> if a relationship name, attested in Matilda <i>Hilles</i>, 1327 (Somerset), where the genitival form may signify widowhood; or with plural <i>-s</i> if habitational, attested in Johanne <i>de Hyles</i>, 1379 (Bickerstaffe, Lancashire), and Ricardo <i>del Hyles</i>, 1379 (Great Eccleston, Lancashire); or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, probably the most common form."]},{"name":"Hiller","meanings":["German: metronymic from <i>Hille</i>, a pet form of the female personal name <i>Hildegund</i> (see   Hilke  ).","German: from a masculine personal beginning with the ancient Germanic element <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German: variant of <b>Hüller</b> (see   Huller  )."]},{"name":"Hil","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hill  .","Dutch (<b>Van den Hil</b>): topographic name from <i>hil, hul</i> ‘hill’, particularly in the sense of a <i>flight hill</i> above sea level in the southwestern Netherlands."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Hill was born about 1460, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1460–":"umbes 1460–Surnud","1478–1509":"1478–1509","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1478":"1478","1460":"1460","1509":"1509","about 1460":"umbes 1460","Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1460–":"noin 1460–Kuollut","1478–1509":"1478–1509","1460–Male":"1460–Kuollut","1478":"1478","1460":"1460","1509":"1509","about 1460":"noin 1460","Kent, England":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1460–":"environ 1460–Décédé","1478–1509":"1478–1509","1460–Male":"1460–Décédé","1478":"1478","1460":"1460","1509":"1509","about 1460":"environ 1460","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert Hill est né environ 1460, à Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"about 1460–":"um 1460–Verstorben","1478–1509":"147